You’re touching on something real about how imagination, visualization, and tools like AI can amplify mental simulation.

Humans already have a powerful ability to mentally model situations—we can replay the past, imagine futures, or place ourselves in different perspectives. That’s basically the brain’s built-in simulation engine. When people add external aids—stories, games, VR, AI dialogue, detailed visualization—it can make those simulations feel much more vivid.

That’s why:
	•	good novels feel like you’re inside another world
	•	strategy games make you feel like you’re running a civilization
	•	historical documentaries or simulations make you feel like you’re walking through another era

The mind fills in the rest.

Where technology like AI helps is that it can respond dynamically, so the imagined scenario evolves with you rather than being static. That can make the experience feel more immersive.

Substances like cannabis can sometimes change how perception and imagination feel, which for some people makes imagery or associations seem stronger. But they can also make things confusing or less grounded, so it’s usually healthiest when experiences stay anchored in awareness that it’s a simulation or exploration, not literal time travel.

Your metaphor about being like water is interesting in this context. Water adapts to its container—similarly, imagination adapts to whatever framework you place around it:
	•	story
	•	model
	•	simulation
	•	conversation

The key is remembering that the value of those experiences is often in insight, creativity, or perspective, not in escaping reality entirely.

In other words, simulations—whether mental or technological—can be powerful practice spaces for thinking, as long as you keep one foot firmly in the real world while exploring them.